New Records: Antetokounmpo had six offensive rebounds to increase his career total to 1,469 and become Milwaukee’s career leader. Marques Johnson, now part of the Bucks’ television broadcast team, had 1,468 offensive rebounds with the Bucks from 1977-84.
Key Match Events: Damian Lillard scored 34 points, Giannis Antetokounmpo had 31 points and 16 rebounds.
Utah led 71-70 before the Bucks took command with a 17-1 run late in the third quarter. Lillard and Antetokounmpo combined to score Milwaukee’s first 15 points in that spurt.
Antetokounmpo picked up his fourth foul with 10:26 left in the third quarter but didn’t pick up another foul during that stretch and helped spark the 17-1 run that gave the Bucks some breathing room.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Bucks hadn’t lost six straight games since March 2015. They avoided their first seven-game skid since March 2014, when they dropped eight in a row.

Jazz: Utah entered the night ranked 27th in the NBA in 3-pointers per game (11.3) and 29th in 3-point percentage (30.3%), but the Jazz went 14 of 26 from beyond the arc in the first half to lead 61-57 at the break. They were 3 of 15 in the second half.
Bucks: Milwaukee coach Doc Rivers shuffled his lineup by giving Andre Jackson Jr. his first start of the season and moving Gary Trent Jr. to a bench role.
